<h1>@HI{{ni suru}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Aistem{{}} @HI{{ku}}<strong>@HI{{suru}}</strong>
<li> @Anastem{{}} @HI{{ni}}<strong>@HI{{suru}}</strong>
<li> @N{{}} <strong>@HI{{ni suru}}</strong>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<strong>@HI{{ni suru}}</strong> means that someone turns something into a certain state.
</br>

<strong>@N{{}}@HI{{ni suru}}</strong> can also mean that someone has decided on something.
</br>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{metropolis^roof}}wo kirei<strong>ni shimasu</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    I will clean my room.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{salt}}no @KJ{{quantity}}wo @KJ{{half^part}}<strong>ni shimasu</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    I will reduce the amount of salt by half.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{sound}}wo @KJ{{large}}kiku shimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    I will turn up the volume.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    A: @HI{{anataha @KJ{{what}}<strong>ni shimasuka</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    B: @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha @KT{{sute-ki}}<strong>ni shimasu</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    A: What will you have?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    B: I'll have steak.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{mount^rice*field}}sanha @KT{{amerika}}no @KJ{{car}}<strong>ni shimashita</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    Mr. Okada has decided on an American car.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<strong>@HI{{ni suru}}</strong> usually follows a noun although it can follow a noun plus particle.
<p></p>

If the tense is nonpast it implies that the decision has just been taken. If it is past, then it is ambiguous
as to whether the decision has yet been enacted.
<p></p>

@HI{{ni kimeru}} has the same meaning and can be used interchangeably with <strong>@HI{{ni suru}}</strong>, although @HI{{ni kimeru}}
is usually used only when the decision is considered to be important.
<p></p>

